5–Male":"1525–Deceased","1530–Female":"1530–Deceased","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1525":"1525","abt 1555":"about 1555","1555":"1555","about 1525":"about 1525","1530":"1530","1505":"1505","abt 1530":"about 1530","1504":"1504","Aberdeen, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","Nethermains, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Fifeshire, Scotland, Dalgety":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Steinsone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish, English:  see  Steenson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Steenson","meanings":["Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish   Steensen  .","Scottish and English: shortened form of   Stevenson  . Compare   Steen   5,   Stenson   1."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eglinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Scottish: locative name from Eglinton in Kilwinning (Ayrs). This is the usual source of the surname.","2  English:  see  Eglington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eggleton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Eggleton (Herefordshire) or Egleton (Rutland), both named in Old English as ‘settlement associated with Ecgwulf or Ecgel’."]},{"name":"Eglington","meanings":["1  English: perhaps a variant of   Eggleton  . Note that Eggleton (Herefs) is recorded as  <i>Eglingtone</i> in 1212.","2  Scottish:  see  Eglinton  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"James Eglinton Steinsone was born in 1505, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Jonnet Pattersone. He died in 1555, in Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1505–1555":"1505–1555","1504–1555":"1504–1555","1525–Male":"1525–Surnud","1530–Female":"1530–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1525":"1525","abt 1555":"umbes 1555","1555":"1555","about 1525":"umbes 1525","1530":"1530","1505":"1505","abt 1530":"umbes 1530","1504":"1504","Aberdeen, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Nethermains, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Š